<p>A <b>field goal</b> (<b>FG</b>) is a means of scoring in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gridiron_football" title=3D"Gridiron football">gr=
idiron football</a>. To score a field goal, the team in possession of the b=
all must <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Place_kick" title=3D"Plac=
e kick">place kick</a>, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drop_ki=
ck" title=3D"Drop kick">drop kick</a>, the ball through the goal, i.e., bet=
ween the uprights and over the crossbar. Consequently, a field goal cannot =
be scored from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punt_(gridiron_fo=
otball)" title=3D"Punt (gridiron football)">punt</a>, as the ball must touc=
h the ground at one point after the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Snap_(gridiron_football)" title=3D"Snap (gridiron football)">snap</a> and=
 before it is kicked in order to be a valid field goal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#=
cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> The entire ball must pass through the vertical plan=
e of the goal, which is the area above the crossbar and between the upright=
s or, if above the uprights, between their outside edges.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goa=
l#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> American football requires that a field goal must=
 only come during a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Play_from_scri=
mmage" title=3D"Play from scrimmage">play from scrimmage</a> (except in the=
 case of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fair_catch_kick" title=
=3D"Fair catch kick">fair catch kick</a>) while Canadian football retains o=
pen field kicks and thus field goals may be scored at any time from anywher=
e on the field and by any player. The vast majority of field goals, in both=
 codes, are placekicked. Drop-kicked field goals were common in the early d=
ays of gridiron football but are almost never attempted in modern times. A =
field goal may also be scored through a fair catch kick, but this is also e=
xtremely rare. In most leagues, a successful field goal awards three points=
 (a notable exception is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six-man_f=
ootball" title=3D"Six-man football">six-man football</a> in which, due to t=
he small number of players available to stop the opposing team from blockin=
g the kick, a field goal is worth four points).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_not=
e-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>Since a field goal is worth only three points, as opposed to a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Touchdown" title=3D"Touchdown">touchdow=
n</a>, which is worth six points (a one- or two-point <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conversion_(gridiron_football)" title=3D"Conversion (gr=
idiron football)">conversion</a> can also be added) , it is usually only at=
tempted in specific situations, such as when the offense has reached its fi=
nal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Down_(gridiron_football)" titl=
e=3D"Down (gridiron football)">down</a> but has advanced the ball into <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal_range" title=3D"Field goal =
range">field goal range</a>, or when there is not enough time left in the h=
alf to score a touchdown.
</p><p>The goal structure consists of a horizontal crossbar suspended 10 fe=
et (3.0&nbsp;m) above the ground, with two vertical goalposts 18&nbsp;feet =
6&nbsp;inches (5.64&nbsp;m) apart extending vertically from each end of the=
 crossbar.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In American football,=
 the goals are centered on each end line; in Canadian football, they are ce=
ntered on each goal line. In order for a field goal to be scored, or to be =
"good", the entire ball must pass through the rectangular plane formed by t=
he bottom horizontal crossbar and two vertical uprights formed by the goalp=
ost. If a field goal fails to pass through this plane, it is "no good" and =
no score is awarded.
</p><p>If a team scores a field goal, they <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Kickoff_(gridiron_football)" title=3D"Kickoff (gridiron football)"=
>kickoff</a> to return possession of the ball to the opposing team. If a fi=
eld goal attempt is unsuccessful, possession of the ball is turned over to =
the opposing team where the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_o=
f_scrimmage" title=3D"Line of scrimmage">line of scrimmage</a> of the field=
 goal attempt was in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_=
Collegiate_Athletic_Association" title=3D"National Collegiate Athletic Asso=
ciation">NCAA</a>, or at the <b>spot of the kick</b>, the spot where the pl=
acekicker made contact with the ball, in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/National_Football_League" title=3D"National Football League">NFL=
</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Strategy">Strategy</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DField_goal&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Strategy"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As a field goal is worth only three points, while a touchdown scores at =
least six (which usually becomes seven with a successful <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conversion_(gridiron_football)" title=3D"Conversion =
(gridiron football)">conversion</a>, and potentially eight with a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-point_conversion" title=3D"Two-point =
conversion">two-point conversion</a>), teams will generally attempt a field=
 goal only in the following situations:
</p>
<ul><li>It is last down (third in Canadian football, fourth down in America=
n football), especially if the offense is more than a yard or two from a ne=
w first down, and within kicking range of the goalposts (about 45 yards at =
the professional level).</li>
<li>In the first half, if there is only enough time remaining to execute ju=
st one more play, regardless of the down.</li>
<li>In the waning moments of the second half, if a successful kick will win=
 or tie the game. In this situation, a team may choose to attempt the field=
 goal on an earlier down or if there is still enough time remaining to exec=
ute more than one play. If there are problems with the snap or hold, the te=
am would be then able to abort the kick attempt (kneel down, or throw an in=
complete pass), and still have at least one down and time remaining to re-a=
ttempt the kick.</li>
<li>In overtime, if a successful field goal wins and ends the game, a team =
may choose to attempt a game-winning kick as soon as they get into field go=
al range (for example, a long pass completion that advances the ball inside=
 the opponent's 20-yard line). In this situation, a team may just decide to=
 try to end the game rather than risk another play that could result in a t=
urnover.</li></ul>
<p>Except in desperate situations, a team will generally attempt field goal=
s only when keeping a drive alive is unlikely, and its <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Placekicker" title=3D"Placekicker">kicker</a> has a si=
gnificant chance of success, as a missed field goal results in a turnover a=
t the spot of the kick (in the NFL) or at the line of scrimmage (in the NCA=
A). In American high school rules and Canadian football, where a missed fie=
ld goal is treated the same as a punt, most teams still opt not to attempt =
field goals from very long range since field goal formations are not conduc=
ive to covering kick returns. Even under ideal conditions, the best profess=
ional kickers historically had difficulty making kicks longer than 50 yards=
 consistently.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-battista_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-battista-5"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> If a team chooses not to attempt a field goal on their last down, they c=
an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punt_(gridiron_football)" title=
=3D"Punt (gridiron football)">punt</a> to the other team. A punt cannot sco=
re any points in American football unless the receiving team touches the ba=
ll first and the kicking team recovers it (though it can result in a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_(football)" title=3D"Single (foot=
ball)">single</a> in Canadian football), but it may push the other team bac=
k toward its own end.
</p><p>The longest field goal kick in NFL history is 68 yards, a record set=
 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cam_Little" title=3D"Cam Littl=
e">Cam Little</a> on 2 November 2025, which broke the record previously hel=
d by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Tucker" title=3D"Justi=
n Tucker">Justin Tucker</a> (2021) at 66 yards.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_not=
e-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cam_Little" title=
=3D"Cam Little">Cam Little</a> kicked a 70-yard field goal in a preseason g=
ame in 2025.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The record in the C=
FL is 63 yards, set by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergio_Cast=
illo" title=3D"Sergio Castillo">Sergio Castillo</a> on August 9, 2025, tyin=
g a 24-year-old record by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_McC=
allum_(gridiron_football)" title=3D"Paul McCallum (gridiron football)">Paul=
 McCallum</a>, which was believed for years to have been 62 yards, though e=
vidence confirmed McCallum's kick was actually closer to 63 yards. High sch=
ool, college and most professional football leagues offer only a three-poin=
t field goal; however, some professional leagues have encouraged more rare =
kicks through four-point field goals. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/NFL_Europe" title=3D"NFL Europe">NFL Europe</a> encouraged long field g=
oals of 50 yards or more by making those worth four points instead of three=
 (much like Australian rules' <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supe=
r_Goal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Super Goal">Super Goal</a> or basket=
ball's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-point_field_goal" tit=
le=3D"Three-point field goal">three-point line</a>), a rule since adopted b=
y the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stars_Football_League" title=
=3D"Stars Football League">Stars Football League</a>. Similarly, the sport =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arena_football" title=3D"Arena =
football">arena football</a> sought (unsuccessfully) to repopularize the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drop_kick" title=3D"Drop kick">drop =
kick</a> by making that worth four points; it failed since only one kicker =
(<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Mitchell_(kicker)" title=3D=
"Brian Mitchell (kicker)">Brian Mitchell</a>) was able to do it with any se=
mblance of proficiency. (In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six-ma=
n_football" title=3D"Six-man football">six-man football</a>, all field goal=
s are worth four points instead of the usual three.) The overall field goal=
 percentage during the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_NFL_se=
ason" title=3D"2010 NFL season">2010 NFL season</a> was 82.3%. In compariso=
n, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jan_Stenerud" title=3D"Jan Sten=
erud">Jan Stenerud</a>, one of only three pure kickers in the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro_Football_Hall_of_Fame" title=3D"Pro Footbal=
l Hall of Fame">Pro Football Hall of Fame</a> (along with fellow placekicke=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morten_Andersen" title=3D"Morten=
 Andersen">Morten Andersen</a> and punter <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Ray_Guy" title=3D"Ray Guy">Ray Guy</a>), had a career field goal pe=
rcentage of 66.8% from 1967 to 1985.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-battista_5-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_not=
e-battista-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
