></span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Field_Goal.ogv" class=
=3D"mw-file-magnify"></a><figcaption>Video of a successful field goal try.<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>When a team decides to attempt a field goal, it will generally line up i=
n a very tight formation, with all but two players lined up along or near t=
he line of scrimmage: the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Placekic=
ker" title=3D"Placekicker">placekicker</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Holder_(gridiron_football)" title=3D"Holder (gridiron foot=
ball)">holder</a>. The holder is usually the team's <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Punter_(football_position)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Punter (football position)">punter</a> or backup <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Quarterback" title=3D"Quarterback">quarterback</a>.<sup =
class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap=
;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" =
title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs referen=
ces to reliable sources. (January 2011)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</s=
up> Instead of the regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_=
(American_football)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Center (American footba=
ll)">center</a>, a team may have a dedicated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Long_snapper" title=3D"Long snapper">long snapper</a> trained es=
pecially to snap the ball on placekick attempts and punts.
</p><p>The holder usually lines up seven to eight yards behind the line of =
scrimmage, with the kicker a few yards behind him. Upon receiving the snap,=
 the holder holds the ball against the ground vertically, with the stitches=
 away from the kicker. The kicker begins his approach during the snap, so t=
he snapper and holder have little margin for error. A split-second mistake =
can disrupt the entire attempt. Depending on the level of play, the ball, u=
pon reaching the holder, is held up by either the aid of a small rubber "te=
e" (all ranks up to the high school level, which is not the same as the kic=
koff tee, but rather a small platform, and comes in either 1- or 2-inch var=
ieties) or is placed on the ground (in college and at the professional leve=
l).=20
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Dustin_Hopkins_(44604555784).=
jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org=
/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Dustin_Hopkins_%2844604555784%29.jpg/250px-Du=
stin_Hopkins_%2844604555784%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"186" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"5361" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"3994"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dustin_=
Hopkins" title=3D"Dustin Hopkins">Dustin Hopkins</a> of the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_Redskins" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Washington Redskins">Washington Redskins</a> attempts a field goal agai=
nst the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carolina_Panthers" title=
=3D"Carolina Panthers">Carolina Panthers</a> in 2018</figcaption></figure>
<p>The measurement of a field goal's distance is from the goalpost to the p=
oint where the ball was positioned for the kick by the holder. In American =
football, where the goalpost is located at the back of the end zone (above =
the end line), the ten yards of the end zone are added to the yard line dis=
tance at the spot of the hold.
</p><p>Until the 1960s, placekickers approached the ball <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Placekicker#Kicking_style" title=3D"Placekicker">str=
aight on</a>, with the toe making first contact with the ball. The techniqu=
e of kicking the ball "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association=
_football_tactics_and_skills" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Association fo=
otball tactics and skills">soccer-style</a>", by approaching the ball at an=
 angle and kicking it with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ins=
tep" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Instep">instep</a>, was introduced by <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungary" title=3D"Hungary">Hungaria=
n</a>-born kicker <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_Gogolak" ti=
tle=3D"Pete Gogolak">Pete Gogolak</a> in the 1960s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite=
_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Reflecting his roots in European soccer, Gogolak observ=
ed that kicking the ball at an angle could cover more distance than kicking=
 straight-on; he played college football at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Cornell_Big_Red_football" title=3D"Cornell Big Red football">Corn=
ell</a> and made his pro debut in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
1964_Buffalo_Bills_season" title=3D"1964 Buffalo Bills season">1964</a> wit=
h the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buffalo_Bills" title=3D"Buff=
alo Bills">Buffalo Bills</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/1964_American_Football_League_season" title=3D"1964 American Football Lea=
gue season">AFL</a>; his younger brother <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Charlie_Gogolak" title=3D"Charlie Gogolak">Charlie</a> was also an N=
FL kicker. The soccer-style kick gained popularity and was nearly universal=
 by the late 1970s; the last full-time straight-on kicker in the NFL was <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Moseley" title=3D"Mark Moseley"=
>Mark Moseley</a>, who retired in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
1986_Cleveland_Browns_season" title=3D"1986 Cleveland Browns season">1986</=
a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Successful_field_goals">Suc=
cessful field goals</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DField_goal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section=
: Successful field goals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>If there is any time left in the half, the method of resuming play after=
 a successful field goal varies between leagues.
</p>

<dl class=3D"glossary">
<dt id=3D"national_football_league_and_most_professional_leagues_and_the_na=
tional_collegiate_athletic_association"><dfn>National Football League and m=
ost professional leagues and the National Collegiate Athletic Association</=
dfn></dt>
<dd>The scored-against team receives a kickoff.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_not=
e-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd>

<dt id=3D"national_federation_of_high_schools"><dfn>National Federation of =
High Schools</dfn></dt>
<dd>The scored-against team can choose to either receive a kickoff or kick =
off themselves. (In practice, almost all choose to receive.)</dd>

<dt id=3D"canadian_football_league"><dfn>Canadian Football League</dfn></dt=
>
<dd>The scored-against team may elect to either kick off from their 30-yard=
 line, receive a kickoff from the opponents' 30-yard line, or scrimmage fro=
m their own 40-yard line. In the last three minutes of the fourth quarter, =
the scoring team kicks off from their 30-yard line.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cit=
e_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> The option of scrimmaging (no kickoff), first instit=
uted in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1975_CFL_season" title=3D"=
1975 CFL season">1975</a>, was eliminated in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/2009_CFL_season" title=3D"2009 CFL season">2009</a>, but the cha=
nge proved unpopular and was reinstated the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/2010_CFL_season" title=3D"2010 CFL season">following season</a>.<=
/dd>

<dt id=3D"football_canada"><dfn>Football Canada</dfn></dt>
<dd>The scored-against team may elect to either kick off from their 35-yard=
 line, receive a kickoff from the opponent's 45-yard line, or scrimmage fro=
m their own 35-yard line.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd=
>

</dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Missed_field_goals">Missed =
field goals</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Field_goal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Missed=
 field goals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>A missed field goal is said to be "no good" if the kicked ball does not =
cross between the uprights and over the crossbar of the goal posts. If it m=
isses to the side of the uprights, it may be called "wide left" or "wide ri=
ght". A field goal attempt may be described as "short" if it does not have =
sufficient distance to go over the cross bar. Some commentators will only d=
escribe a field goal attempt as being short if it appears to have been aime=
d correctly while others will describe an attempt appearing to lack both ac=
curacy and distance as being both wide and short.
</p><p>If a field goal attempt is missed, and the ball does not go out of b=
ounds and has not been ruled dead by a referee, then a defensive player may=
 advance the ball, as with a punt or kickoff. This type of play usually occ=
urs either during an extremely long field goal attempt or if the attempt is=
 blocked. If there is a significant likelihood of a miss and the strategic =
game situation warrants it, the defense places a player downfield, in or ne=
ar their end zone, to catch the ball. The risk in this is that the return m=
an may be tackled deep in his own territory, at a considerably worse positi=
on than he could have gotten by letting the ball go dead (see below); furth=
ermore, should the returner fumble the ball, the kicking team can recover i=
t and gain a new set of downs (the advantage is that the kicking team is li=
ned up very close together to stop kick blockers, and not spread across the=
 field like a kickoff or punt team, and is therefore in poor position to de=
fend the return). Thus, teams will usually return a kick only towards the e=
nd of a half (when the kick will be the final play) or in a particularly de=
sperate situation.
</p><p>If a ball caroms off one of the goal posts or the crossbar but lands=
 in the field of play, the ball is considered dead and cannot be returned. =
(This is not the case in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arena_foo=
tball" title=3D"Arena football">arena football</a>, where large "rebound ne=
ts" surround the goal posts for the explicit purpose of keeping the ball in=
 play.) However, if the ball continues into the goal after caroming, the sc=
ore counts. If the ball re-enters the field of play after crossing the vert=
ical plane of the goal, the score also counts; this is now known as the "<a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil_Dawson" title=3D"Phil Dawson">P=
hil Dawson</a> rule" after the eponymous player scored a game-tying field g=
oal that rebounded off the back support of the goal and back into the field=
 of play.
</p><p>Situations where the defense does not return a missed field goal var=
y between leagues and levels of play:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1228772891">
<dl class=3D"glossary">
<dt id=3D"national_football_league"><dfn>National Football League</dfn></dt=
>
<dd>Missed field goals attempted from the defending team's 20-yard line or =
closer result in the defense taking possession at their 20-yard line. Misse=
d field goals attempted from behind the 20-yard line result in the opposing=
 team taking possession at the <b>spot of the kick</b>. (From 1974=E2=80=93=
1993, the opposing team would take possession at the line of scrimmage, unl=
ess the kick was attempted from inside the 20-yard line, in which case the =
opposing team would take possession at the 20-yard line. Prior to 1974, a m=
issed field goal was treated the same as a punt, and the kicking team could=
 down the ball in the field of play if it did not cross the goal line; if t=
he unsuccessful attempt crossed the goal line, it was a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Touchback" title=3D"Touchback">touchback</a>, unless =
the defense ran the ball out of the end zone, which did not become legal un=
til <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1971_NFL_season" title=3D"1971=
 NFL season">1971</a>.)</dd>

<dt id=3D"ncaa"><dfn>NCAA</dfn></dt>
<dd>The opposing team takes possession at the line of scrimmage rather than=
 at the spot of the kick. If the line of scrimmage is inside the 20-yard li=
ne, the opposing team takes possession at the 20.<sup class=3D"noprint Inli=
ne-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Ci=
tation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sourc=
es. (January 2011)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></dd>

<dt id=3D"high_school"><dfn>High school</dfn></dt>
<dd>Under NFHS (high school) rules (except Texas, which plays largely by NC=
AA rules), a field goal attempt is no different from any other scrimmage ki=
ck (e.g. punt or drop kick). If the field goal attempt is no good and enter=
s the end zone it is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Touchback" =
title=3D"Touchback">touchback</a> (NFHS rules do not allow a scrimmage kick=
 or free kick to be advanced if it crosses the goal line). If the ball beco=
mes dead on the field the defensive team will next put the ball in play fro=
m that point. If a field goal is blocked behind the line of scrimmage eithe=
r team may pick it up and return it (see below).</dd>

<dt id=3D"canadian_football"><dfn>Canadian football</dfn></dt>
<dd>If the defense does not return a missed field goal out of the end zone,=
 or if a missed field goal attempt goes out the back of end zone, then the =
kicking team scores a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_(foot=
ball)" title=3D"Single (football)">single point</a>. This sometimes results=
 in the team on defense stationing their punter behind the goal posts to pu=
nt the ball out of the end zone, in case of a missed field-goal attempt, to=
 preserve a victory or tie. Also, a missed field goal may be played by any =
onside player on the kicking team (onside players being the kicker and anyo=
ne behind him at the time of the kick). It is risky to have anyone position=
ed behind the kicker when the ball is being kicked since those players woul=
d be unable to help prevent the defending players from blocking the kick; h=
owever, on occasion teams might intentionally miss a field goal in hope of =
recovering the ball in the end zone for a touchdown.

Returning a missed field goal is much more likely in Canadian football than=
 in American rules for a few reasons. First, since the goal posts are on th=
e goal line in front of a 20-yard end zone (rather than at the back of a 10=
-yard end zone), a missed field goal is much less likely to go out of bound=
s while in the air. Also, not returning the ball out of the end zone result=
s in the defense conceding a single point, which may be crucial in a close =
game.  Moreover, the wider field of the Canadian game makes the average ret=
urn longer (in terms of yardage). However, many Canadian football coaches j=
udge that conceding a single and taking possession at the 35-yard line is p=
referable to returning a missed field goal and avoiding a single at the cos=
t of poor field position.</dd>
</dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Blocked_field_goals">Blocke=
d field goals</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DField_goal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Blo=
cked field goals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fresno_State_Texas_Aggies_Blo=
cked_Kick.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wik=
imedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Fresno_State_Texas_Aggies_Blocked_K=
ick.jpg/250px-Fresno_State_Texas_Aggies_Blocked_Kick.jpg" decoding=3D"async=
" width=3D"250" height=3D"166" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D=
"1280" data-file-height=3D"851"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Fresno_State_Bulldogs_football" title=3D"Fresno State Bul=
ldogs football">Fresno State Bulldogs</a> block a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Texas_A%26M_Aggies_football" title=3D"Texas A&amp;M Aggies =
football">Texas A&amp;M</a> field goal attempt.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Occasionally, the defense will succeed in blocking a field goal. If the =
ball falls in or behind the neutral zone, it is treated like a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fumble" title=3D"Fumble">fumble</a> and can be=
 advanced by either team. If the ball instead falls forward beyond the neut=
ral zone, it is treated like a missed field goal under <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#Missed_field_goals">the rules explained abo=
ve</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DField_goal&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the early days of football, kicking was emphasized. In <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1883_college_football_season" title=3D"1883 coll=
ege football season">1883</a>, the scoring system was devised with field go=
als counting for five points, touchdowns two points, and conversions four p=
oints.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sumner_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-Sumner-13"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the=
 following year touchdowns doubled in value to four, and rose to five in 18=
98. Meanwhile, the value of a conversion fell to two points in 1884 and one=
 point in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1898_college_football_se=
ason" title=3D"1898 college football season">1898</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-S=
umner_13-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fi=
eld_goal#cite_note-Sumner-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (In 1958, the NCAA created the tw=
o-point conversion for conversions scored via run or pass; the NFL followed=
 suit in 1994.) Field goals were devalued to four points in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1904_college_football_season" title=3D"1904 colle=
ge football season">1904</a>, and then to the modern three points in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1909_college_football_season" title=3D"1=
909 college football season">1909</a>. The touchdown was changed to six poi=
nts in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1912_college_football_seaso=
n" title=3D"1912 college football season">1912</a> in American football; th=
e Canadian game followed suit in 1956.
</p><p>The spot of the conversion has also changed through the years. In <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1924_college_football_season" title=
=3D"1924 college football season">1924</a>, NCAA rules spotted the conversi=
on at the 3-yard line, before moving it back to the 5-yard line in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1925_college_football_season" title=3D"19=
25 college football season">1925</a>. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/1929_college_football_season" title=3D"1929 college football season"=
>1929</a>, the spot was moved up to the 2-yard line, matching the NFL. In 1=
968, the NCAA diverged from the NFL rules and moved the spot back to the or=
iginal 3-yard line. Canadian rules originally spotted the conversion at the=
 5-yard line, which remains closer than in the American code (for kicked co=
nversions) as the goalposts are at the front of the end zone.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_NFL_season" title=
=3D"2015 NFL season">2015</a>, to make conversion kicks harder, the NFL and=
 CFL moved the line of scrimmage for conversion kicks to the 15- and 25-yar=
d lines, respectively. (The CFL also moved the spot for two-point conversio=
n attempts to the 3-yard line, while then NFL remained at the 2-yard line.)
</p><p>The goalposts were originally located on the goal line; this led to =
many injuries and sometimes interfered with play. The NCAA moved the goal p=
osts to the rear of the end zone in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/1927_college_football_season" title=3D"1927 college football season">1927=
</a>. The NFL (still following NCAA rules at the time) followed suit, but m=
oved the posts back to the goal line starting in the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/1932_NFL_Playoff_Game" title=3D"1932 NFL Playoff Game">1=
932 NFL Playoff Game</a>, a change made necessary by the size of the indoor=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Stadium" title=3D"Chicago=
 Stadium">Chicago Stadium</a> and kept when the NFL rules stopped mirroring=
 the NCAA rules in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1933_NFL_season=
" title=3D"1933 NFL season">1933</a>. The NFL kept the goal posts at the go=
al line until 1974, when they were moved back to the rear of the end zone, =
where they have remained since. This was partly a result of the narrowed ha=
shmark distance made in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1972_NFL_s=
eason" title=3D"1972 NFL season">1972</a> (making them the same width as th=
e goalposts), which had made for easier field-goal angles. The Canadian gam=
e still has posts on the goal line.
</p><p>The width of the goalposts and the hashmarks have also varied throug=
hout the years. In 1959, the NCAA goalposts were widened to 23&nbsp;feet 4&=
nbsp;inches (7.11&nbsp;m), the standard width for high school posts today. =
In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1991_NCAA_Division_I-A_football=
_season" title=3D"1991 NCAA Division I-A football season">1991</a>, the col=
lege goalposts were reduced in width to 18&nbsp;ft 6&nbsp;in (5.64&nbsp;m),=
 matching the NFL. For the 1991 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/1992_NCAA_Division_I-A_football_season" title=3D"1992 NCAA Division I-A f=
ootball season">1992</a> seasons, this meant potentially severe angles for =
short field goal attempts, since the hashmark width remained at 53&nbsp;ft =
4&nbsp;in (16.26&nbsp;m). In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1993_=
NCAA_Division_I-A_football_season" title=3D"1993 NCAA Division I-A football=
 season">1993</a>, the NCAA narrowed the distance between the hashmarks to =
40&nbsp;ft (12.19&nbsp;m), matching the width of hashmarks in the NFL from =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1945_NFL_season" title=3D"1945 NFL=
 season">1945</a> through <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1971_NFL=
_season" title=3D"1971 NFL season">1971</a>; as mentioned above, the NFL na=
rrowed the hashmarks in 1972 to goalpost width at 18.5 feet (5.64&nbsp;m). =
Canadian hash marks in amateur play are 51 feet (16&nbsp;m) apart, 24 yards=
 from each sideline. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_=
Football_League" title=3D"Canadian Football League">Canadian Football Leagu=
e</a> formerly used this spacing, but narrowed the hash mark spacing to 9 y=
ards (8.2&nbsp;m) in 2022.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-14"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
e Canadian field is 195 feet (59&nbsp;m) in width, 35 feet (11&nbsp;m) wide=
r than the American field.
</p><p>The NFL increased the height of the uprights above the crossbar to 2=
0 feet (6.10&nbsp;m) in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1966_NFL_s=
eason" title=3D"1966 NFL season">1966</a> and 30 feet (9.14&nbsp;m) in 1974=
. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_NFL_season" title=3D"201=
4 NFL season">2014</a>, they were raised five feet to 35 feet (10.67&nbsp;m=
) after the adoption of a proposal by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/New_England_Patriots" title=3D"New England Patriots">New England Patrio=
ts</a> head coach <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Belichick" =
title=3D"Bill Belichick">Bill Belichick</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_not=
e-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The "slingshot" goalpost, having a single post curving 90=C2=B0 up f=
rom the ground to support the crossbar, was invented by Jim Trimble and Joe=
l Rottman in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montreal,_Quebec" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Montreal, Quebec">Montreal, Quebec</a>, Canada.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-tdfcan_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-tdfcan-16"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The first on=
es were built by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcan" title=3D"A=
lcan">Alcan</a> and displayed at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Expo_67" title=3D"Expo 67">Expo 67</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-tdfcan_16-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite=
_note-tdfcan-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-17"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World%27s_fair" title=3D"World's =
fair">world's fair</a> in Montreal. The NFL had standardized its goalposts =
in 1966 and adopted the slingshot for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/1967_NFL_season" title=3D"1967 NFL season">1967</a> season.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-tdfcan_16-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-tdfcan-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The NCAA subsequent=
ly adopted the same rule, but later allowed the use of "offset" goalposts w=
ith the older two-post base. The CFL was the first league to use the slings=
hot goalposts. They debuted in the 2nd game of the CFL's Eastern Conference=
 final in 1966 at Montreal's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autos=
tade" title=3D"Autostade">Autostade</a> because Landsdowne Park (now <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TD_Place_Stadium" title=3D"TD Place Stad=
ium">TD Place Stadium</a>), the home of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Ottawa_Rough_Riders" title=3D"Ottawa Rough Riders">Ottawa Rough Rider=
s</a>, was undergoing renovations. They were also used in the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Cup" title=3D"Grey Cup">Grey Cup</a> the n=
ext week at Vancouver's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empire_Sta=
dium_(Vancouver)" title=3D"Empire Stadium (Vancouver)">Empire Stadium</a>. =
Three schools in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NCAA_Division_I_F=
ootball_Bowl_Subdivision" title=3D"NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivisio=
n">Division I FBS</a> currently use dual-support posts: <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florida_State_Seminoles_football" title=3D"Florida St=
ate Seminoles football">Florida State</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/LSU_Tigers_football" title=3D"LSU Tigers football">LSU</a>, and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_State_Cougars_football" t=
itle=3D"Washington State Cougars football">Washington State</a>. A special =
exemption was allowed by the NFL for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/New_Orleans_Saints" title=3D"New Orleans Saints">New Orleans Saints<=
/a> to use the offset goalposts during the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/2005_New_Orleans_Saints_season" title=3D"2005 New Orleans Saints s=
eason">2005</a> season, when they used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Tiger_Stadium_(LSU)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tiger Stadium (LSU=
)">LSU's stadium</a> for home games <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Effect_of_Hurricane_Katrina_on_the_New_Orleans_Saints" title=3D"Effect of=
 Hurricane Katrina on the New Orleans Saints">after</a> <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurricane_Katrina" title=3D"Hurricane Katrina">Hurric=
ane Katrina</a>.
</p><p>Goalposts at the professional level today are sometimes equipped wit=
h a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_camera" title=3D"Video c=
amera">video camera</a> mounted to the stanchion immediately behind the cen=
ter of the crossbar. Since these cameras are both above and slightly behind=
 the crossbar, a field goal attempt will be judged good if it strikes this =
equipment.
</p><p>A small plastic tee, which can be 1&nbsp;to 2 inches (25=E2=80=9351&=
nbsp;mm) high (smaller than the kickoff tee), may be used for field goals a=
nd extra points in some leagues, including US high schools and Canadian ama=
teur play. The NFL (and most other professional leagues) has never allowed =
the use of tees for field goal kick attempts, having always required kicker=
s to kick off the ground for such attempts (and for extra points; a rare ex=
ception for a U.S.-based pro league to allow the usage of such tees for suc=
h attempts was the original <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United=
_States_Football_League" title=3D"United States Football League">USFL</a> i=
n the 1980s).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_=
goal#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
1948_NCAA_Division_I-A_football_season" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"1948=
 NCAA Division I-A football season">1948</a>, the NCAA authorized the use o=
f the small rubberized kicking tee for extra points and field goals, but ba=
nned them by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_NCAA_Division_I-=
A_football_season" title=3D"1989 NCAA Division I-A football season">1989</a=
>, requiring kicks from the ground, as in the NFL.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite=
_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The CFL=
 allows the use of a tee for field goals and convert kicks, but it is optio=
nal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>During the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_NFL_season"=
 title=3D"2011 NFL season">2011</a> NFL season, a record 90 field goals of =
50 yards or longer were made.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-teamrankings.com_23-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_goal#cite_n=
ote-teamrankings.com-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/2012_NFL_season" title=3D"2012 NFL season">2012</a>, this record was =
raised to 92 field goals of 50 yards or longer.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-teamrank=
ings.com_23-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Field_goal#cite_note-teamrankings.com-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
